{"line":"{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01HH4XxkHHoMvAzrXfEaq1Ly\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→# cc-manager\\n     2→\\n     3→`cc-manager` is an interactive terminal app that puts a **controller agent** (Codex CLI) in front of **Claude Code**.\\n     4→\\n     5→The visible loop is:\\n     6→\\n     7→1. **User** sends a message in the shell.\\n     8→2. **Controller** (Codex) decides whether to:\\n     9→   - reply directly and stop, or\\n    10→   - launch **Claude Code** with the next worker prompt.\\n    11→3. **Claude Code** runs and its output is streamed live in the terminal.\\n    12→4. When Claude finishes, the **Controller** runs again, reviews the result and repository state, and decides the next Claude message or emits **STOP**.\\n    13→5. The shell stays open after **STOP** and waits for the next user instruction.\\n    14→\\n    15→That makes the controller behave like a developer using Claude Code on behalf of the human manager.\\n    16→\\n    17→## What this implementation guarantees\\n    18→\\n    19→- The shell remains open after `STOP`.\\n    20→- The controller can answer simple messages directly without launching Claude Code.\\n    21→- When the controller delegates, the app prints the exact Claude prompt it is sending.\\n    22→- Claude output is streamed in real time.\\n    23→- After Claude exits, the controller gets another turn and can inspect the repository before deciding the next step.\\n    24→- The same Claude session is reused across worker turns in the same run.\\n    25→- Runs are persisted under `.cc-manager/runs/<run-id>` and can be resumed later.\\n    26→\\n    27→## Install\\n    28→\\n    29→```bash\\n    30→npm install\\n    31→npm link\\n    32→```\\n    33→\\n    34→Node 18.17+ is required.\\n    35→\\n    36→## Interactive shell\\n    37→\\n    38→Start the shell in the repository you want to manage:\\n    39→\\n    40→```bash\\n    41→cd /path/to/repo\\n    42→cc-manager\\n    43→```\\n    44→\\n    45→You can also point it at another repo/state directory:\\n    46→\\n    47→```bash\\n    48→cc-manager --repo /path/to/repo --state-dir /path/to/state\\n    49→```\\n    50→\\n    51→### Shell behavior\\n    52→\\n    53→- If no run is attached, plain text starts a new run.\\n    54→- If a run is attached, plain text becomes the next user message for that run.\\n    55→- After the controller emits `STOP`, the shell stays attached to the run and waits for the next message.\\n    56→\\n    57→### Shell commands\\n    58→\\n    59→```text\\n    60→/help                Show help\\n    61→/new <message>       Start a brand new run and send the first message\\n    62→/resume <run-id>     Attach to an existing run\\n    63→/use <run-id>        Alias for /resume\\n    64→/run                 Continue an interrupted request in the current run\\n    65→/status              Show status for the attached run\\n    66→/list                List saved runs\\n    67→/logs [n]            Show the last n event lines for the attached run\\n    68→/detach              Detach from the current run\\n    69→/quit                Exit the shell\\n    70→```\\n    71→\\n    72→## One-shot usage\\n    73→\\n    74→Start a new run, process until `STOP`, then exit:\\n    75→\\n    76→```bash\\n    77→cc-manager run \\\"Please do fixes in this repository until all unit tests pass\\\"\\n    78→```\\n    79→\\n    80→Resume an existing run with another user message:\\n    81→\\n    82→```bash\\n    83→cc-manager resume <run-id> \\\"Good job. Thank you\\\"\\n    84→```\\n    85→\\n    86→Show run status:\\n    87→\\n    88→```bash\\n    89→cc-manager status <run-id>\\n    90→```\\n    91→\\n    92→Show recent events:\\n    93→\\n    94→```bash\\n    95→cc-manager logs <run-id> --tail 80\\n    96→```\\n    97→\\n    98→List runs:\\n    99→\\n   100→```bash\\n   101→cc-manager list\\n   102→```\\n   103→\\n   104→Verify binaries:\\n   105→\\n   106→```bash\\n   107→cc-manager doctor\\n   108→```\\n   109→\\n   110→## Important defaults\\n   111→\\n   112→### Controller (Codex)\\n   113→\\n   114→By default the controller uses:\\n   115→\\n   116→- `codex exec`\\n   117→- `codex exec resume <session-id>` after the first controller turn\\n   118→- `--json`\\n   119→- `--output-schema`\\n   120→- `--output-last-message`\\n   121→- `--ask-for-approval never`\\n   122→- `--sandbox workspace-write`\\n   123→\\n   124→The controller prompt explicitly tells Codex to **inspect and verify only** and to avoid editing files itself. Claude Code is the worker that performs actual repository changes.\\n   125→\\n   126→### Worker (Claude Code)\\n   127→\\n   128→By default the worker uses:\\n   129→\\n   130→- `claude -p`\\n   131→- `--output-format stream-json`\\n   132→- `--verbose`\\n   133→- `--include-partial-messages`\\n   134→- `--session-id <uuid>` for the first worker turn\\n   135→- `--resume <session-id>` on later worker turns\\n   136→- `--allowedTools \\\"Bash,Read,Edit\\\"`\\n   137→- a default appended system prompt that encourages concise progress narration\\n   138→\\n   139→## Useful options\\n   140→\\n   141→```text\\n   142→--repo <path>\\n   143→--state-dir <path>\\n   144→--codex-bin <path>\\n   145→--claude-bin <path>\\n   146→--controller-model <name>\\n   147→--controller-profile <name>\\n   148→--controller-sandbox <read-only|workspace-write|danger-full-access>\\n   149→--controller-config <key=value>            repeatable\\n   150→--controller-skip-git-repo-check\\n   151→--controller-extra-instructions <text>\\n   152→--worker-model <name>\\n   153→--worker-session-id <uuid>\\n   154→--worker-allowed-tools <rules>\\n   155→--worker-tools <rules>\\n   156→--worker-disallowed-tools <rules>\\n   157→--worker-permission-prompt-tool <name>\\n   158→--worker-max-turns <n>\\n   159→--worker-max-budget-usd <amount>\\n   160→--worker-add-dir <path>                    repeatable\\n   161→--worker-append-system-prompt <text>\\n   162→--raw-events\\n   163→--quiet\\n   164→```\\n   165→\\n   166→## Saved run layout\\n   167→\\n   168→Each run is stored under:\\n   169→\\n   170→```text\\n   171→.cc-manager/\\n   172→  runs/\\n   173→    <run-id>/\\n   174→      manifest.json\\n   175→      controller-decision.schema.json\\n   176→      events.jsonl\\n   177→      transcript.jsonl\\n   178→      requests/\\n   179→        req-0001/\\n   180→          loop-0001/\\n   181→            controller.prompt.txt\\n   182→            controller.stdout.log\\n   183→            controller.stderr.log\\n   184→            controller.final.json\\n   185→            worker.prompt.txt\\n   186→            worker.stdout.log\\n   187→            worker.stderr.log\\n   188→            worker.final.json\\n   189→```\\n   190→\\n   191→## Tests\\n   192→\\n   193→This repo includes fake Codex and Claude binaries plus integration tests that verify the exact visible control loop:\\n   194→\\n   195→- greeting -> controller replies directly -> `STOP`\\n   196→- real work -> controller delegates -> Claude streams -> controller reviews -> controller delegates again -> `STOP`\\n   197→- follow-up user message on the same run -> controller replies directly -> `STOP`\\n   198→\\n   199→Run them with:\\n   200→\\n   201→```bash\\n   202→npm test\\n   203→```\\n   204→\"}]},\"parent_tool_use_id\":null,\"session_id\":\"076ed951-b233-4f01-9f84-929dcf77822b\",\"uuid\":\"ec1251f4-91f1-47e6-8b8d-17fd60fd735c\",\"tool_use_result\":{\"type\":\"text\",\"file\":{\"filePath\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\Server\\\\Downloads\\\\cc-manager-final\\\\cc-manager\\\\README.md\",\"content\":\"# cc-manager\\n\\n`cc-manager` is an interactive terminal app that puts a **controller agent** (Codex CLI) in front of **Claude Code**.\\n\\nThe visible loop is:\\n\\n1. **User** sends a message in the shell.\\n2. **Controller** (Codex) decides whether to:\\n   - reply directly and stop, or\\n   - launch **Claude Code** with the next worker prompt.\\n3. **Claude Code** runs and its output is streamed live in the terminal.\\n4. When Claude finishes, the **Controller** runs again, reviews the result and repository state, and decides the next Claude message or emits **STOP**.\\n5. The shell stays open after **STOP** and waits for the next user instruction.\\n\\nThat makes the controller behave like a developer using Claude Code on behalf of the human manager.\\n\\n## What this implementation guarantees\\n\\n- The shell remains open after `STOP`.\\n- The controller can answer simple messages directly without launching Claude Code.\\n- When the controller delegates, the app prints the exact Claude prompt it is sending.\\n- Claude output is streamed in real time.\\n- After Claude exits, the controller gets another turn and can inspect the repository before deciding the next step.\\n- The same Claude session is reused across worker turns in the same run.\\n- Runs are persisted under `.cc-manager/runs/<run-id>` and can be resumed later.\\n\\n## Install\\n\\n```bash\\nnpm install\\nnpm link\\n```\\n\\nNode 18.17+ is required.\\n\\n## Interactive shell\\n\\nStart the shell in the repository you want to manage:\\n\\n```bash\\ncd /path/to/repo\\ncc-manager\\n```\\n\\nYou can also point it at another repo/state directory:\\n\\n```bash\\ncc-manager --repo /path/to/repo --state-dir /path/to/state\\n```\\n\\n### Shell behavior\\n\\n- If no run is attached, plain text starts a new run.\\n- If a run is attached, plain text becomes the next user message for that run.\\n- After the controller emits `STOP`, the shell stays attached to the run and waits for the next message.\\n\\n### Shell commands\\n\\n```text\\n/help                Show help\\n/new <message>       Start a brand new run and send the first message\\n/resume <run-id>     Attach to an existing run\\n/use <run-id>        Alias for /resume\\n/run                 Continue an interrupted request in the current run\\n/status              Show status for the attached run\\n/list                List saved runs\\n/logs [n]            Show the last n event lines for the attached run\\n/detach              Detach from the current run\\n/quit                Exit the shell\\n```\\n\\n## One-shot usage\\n\\nStart a new run, process until `STOP`, then exit:\\n\\n```bash\\ncc-manager run \\\"Please do fixes in this repository until all unit tests pass\\\"\\n```\\n\\nResume an existing run with another user message:\\n\\n```bash\\ncc-manager resume <run-id> \\\"Good job. Thank you\\\"\\n```\\n\\nShow run status:\\n\\n```bash\\ncc-manager status <run-id>\\n```\\n\\nShow recent events:\\n\\n```bash\\ncc-manager logs <run-id> --tail 80\\n```\\n\\nList runs:\\n\\n```bash\\ncc-manager list\\n```\\n\\nVerify binaries:\\n\\n```bash\\ncc-manager doctor\\n```\\n\\n## Important defaults\\n\\n### Controller (Codex)\\n\\nBy default the controller uses:\\n\\n- `codex exec`\\n- `codex exec resume <session-id>` after the first controller turn\\n- `--json`\\n- `--output-schema`\\n- `--output-last-message`\\n- `--ask-for-approval never`\\n- `--sandbox workspace-write`\\n\\nThe controller prompt explicitly tells Codex to **inspect and verify only** and to avoid editing files itself. Claude Code is the worker that performs actual repository changes.\\n\\n### Worker (Claude Code)\\n\\nBy default the worker uses:\\n\\n- `claude -p`\\n- `--output-format stream-json`\\n- `--verbose`\\n- `--include-partial-messages`\\n- `--session-id <uuid>` for the first worker turn\\n- `--resume <session-id>` on later worker turns\\n- `--allowedTools \\\"Bash,Read,Edit\\\"`\\n- a default appended system prompt that encourages concise progress narration\\n\\n## Useful options\\n\\n```text\\n--repo <path>\\n--state-dir <path>\\n--codex-bin <path>\\n--claude-bin <path>\\n--controller-model <name>\\n--controller-profile <name>\\n--controller-sandbox <read-only|workspace-write|danger-full-access>\\n--controller-config <key=value>            repeatable\\n--controller-skip-git-repo-check\\n--controller-extra-instructions <text>\\n--worker-model <name>\\n--worker-session-id <uuid>\\n--worker-allowed-tools <rules>\\n--worker-tools <rules>\\n--worker-disallowed-tools <rules>\\n--worker-permission-prompt-tool <name>\\n--worker-max-turns <n>\\n--worker-max-budget-usd <amount>\\n--worker-add-dir <path>                    repeatable\\n--worker-append-system-prompt <text>\\n--raw-events\\n--quiet\\n```\\n\\n## Saved run layout\\n\\nEach run is stored under:\\n\\n```text\\n.cc-manager/\\n  runs/\\n    <run-id>/\\n      manifest.json\\n      controller-decision.schema.json\\n      events.jsonl\\n      transcript.jsonl\\n      requests/\\n        req-0001/\\n          loop-0001/\\n            controller.prompt.txt\\n            controller.stdout.log\\n            controller.stderr.log\\n            controller.final.json\\n            worker.prompt.txt\\n            worker.stdout.log\\n            worker.stderr.log\\n            worker.final.json\\n```\\n\\n## Tests\\n\\nThis repo includes fake Codex and Claude binaries plus integration tests that verify the exact visible control loop:\\n\\n- greeting -> controller replies directly -> `STOP`\\n- real work -> controller delegates -> Claude streams -> controller reviews -> controller delegates again -> `STOP`\\n- follow-up user message on the same run -> controller replies directly -> `STOP`\\n\\nRun them with:\\n\\n```bash\\nnpm test\\n```\\n\",\"numLines\":204,\"startLine\":1,\"totalLines\":204}}}","parsed":{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HH4XxkHHoMvAzrXfEaq1Ly","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# cc-manager\n     2→\n     3→`cc-manager` is an interactive terminal app that puts a **controller agent** (Codex CLI) in front of **Claude Code**.\n     4→\n     5→The visible loop is:\n     6→\n     7→1. **User** sends a message in the shell.\n     8→2. **Controller** (Codex) decides whether to:\n     9→   - reply directly and stop, or\n    10→   - launch **Claude Code** with the next worker prompt.\n    11→3. **Claude Code** runs and its output is streamed live in the terminal.\n    12→4. When Claude finishes, the **Controller** runs again, reviews the result and repository state, and decides the next Claude message or emits **STOP**.\n    13→5. The shell stays open after **STOP** and waits for the next user instruction.\n    14→\n    15→That makes the controller behave like a developer using Claude Code on behalf of the human manager.\n    16→\n    17→## What this implementation guarantees\n    18→\n    19→- The shell remains open after `STOP`.\n    20→- The controller can answer simple messages directly without launching Claude Code.\n    21→- When the controller delegates, the app prints the exact Claude prompt it is sending.\n    22→- Claude output is streamed in real time.\n    23→- After Claude exits, the controller gets another turn and can inspect the repository before deciding the next step.\n    24→- The same Claude session is reused across worker turns in the same run.\n    25→- Runs are persisted under `.cc-manager/runs/<run-id>` and can be resumed later.\n    26→\n    27→## Install\n    28→\n    29→```bash\n    30→npm install\n    31→npm link\n    32→```\n    33→\n    34→Node 18.17+ is required.\n    35→\n    36→## Interactive shell\n    37→\n    38→Start the shell in the repository you want to manage:\n    39→\n    40→```bash\n    41→cd /path/to/repo\n    42→cc-manager\n    43→```\n    44→\n    45→You can also point it at another repo/state directory:\n    46→\n    47→```bash\n    48→cc-manager --repo /path/to/repo --state-dir /path/to/state\n    49→```\n    50→\n    51→### Shell behavior\n    52→\n    53→- If no run is attached, plain text starts a new run.\n    54→- If a run is attached, plain text becomes the next user message for that run.\n    55→- After the controller emits `STOP`, the shell stays attached to the run and waits for the next message.\n    56→\n    57→### Shell commands\n    58→\n    59→```text\n    60→/help                Show help\n    61→/new <message>       Start a brand new run and send the first message\n    62→/resume <run-id>     Attach to an existing run\n    63→/use <run-id>        Alias for /resume\n    64→/run                 Continue an interrupted request in the current run\n    65→/status              Show status for the attached run\n    66→/list                List saved runs\n    67→/logs [n]            Show the last n event lines for the attached run\n    68→/detach              Detach from the current run\n    69→/quit                Exit the shell\n    70→```\n    71→\n    72→## One-shot usage\n    73→\n    74→Start a new run, process until `STOP`, then exit:\n    75→\n    76→```bash\n    77→cc-manager run \"Please do fixes in this repository until all unit tests pass\"\n    78→```\n    79→\n    80→Resume an existing run with another user message:\n    81→\n    82→```bash\n    83→cc-manager resume <run-id> \"Good job. Thank you\"\n    84→```\n    85→\n    86→Show run status:\n    87→\n    88→```bash\n    89→cc-manager status <run-id>\n    90→```\n    91→\n    92→Show recent events:\n    93→\n    94→```bash\n    95→cc-manager logs <run-id> --tail 80\n    96→```\n    97→\n    98→List runs:\n    99→\n   100→```bash\n   101→cc-manager list\n   102→```\n   103→\n   104→Verify binaries:\n   105→\n   106→```bash\n   107→cc-manager doctor\n   108→```\n   109→\n   110→## Important defaults\n   111→\n   112→### Controller (Codex)\n   113→\n   114→By default the controller uses:\n   115→\n   116→- `codex exec`\n   117→- `codex exec resume <session-id>` after the first controller turn\n   118→- `--json`\n   119→- `--output-schema`\n   120→- `--output-last-message`\n   121→- `--ask-for-approval never`\n   122→- `--sandbox workspace-write`\n   123→\n   124→The controller prompt explicitly tells Codex to **inspect and verify only** and to avoid editing files itself. Claude Code is the worker that performs actual repository changes.\n   125→\n   126→### Worker (Claude Code)\n   127→\n   128→By default the worker uses:\n   129→\n   130→- `claude -p`\n   131→- `--output-format stream-json`\n   132→- `--verbose`\n   133→- `--include-partial-messages`\n   134→- `--session-id <uuid>` for the first worker turn\n   135→- `--resume <session-id>` on later worker turns\n   136→- `--allowedTools \"Bash,Read,Edit\"`\n   137→- a default appended system prompt that encourages concise progress narration\n   138→\n   139→## Useful options\n   140→\n   141→```text\n   142→--repo <path>\n   143→--state-dir <path>\n   144→--codex-bin <path>\n   145→--claude-bin <path>\n   146→--controller-model <name>\n   147→--controller-profile <name>\n   148→--controller-sandbox <read-only|workspace-write|danger-full-access>\n   149→--controller-config <key=value>            repeatable\n   150→--controller-skip-git-repo-check\n   151→--controller-extra-instructions <text>\n   152→--worker-model <name>\n   153→--worker-session-id <uuid>\n   154→--worker-allowed-tools <rules>\n   155→--worker-tools <rules>\n   156→--worker-disallowed-tools <rules>\n   157→--worker-permission-prompt-tool <name>\n   158→--worker-max-turns <n>\n   159→--worker-max-budget-usd <amount>\n   160→--worker-add-dir <path>                    repeatable\n   161→--worker-append-system-prompt <text>\n   162→--raw-events\n   163→--quiet\n   164→```\n   165→\n   166→## Saved run layout\n   167→\n   168→Each run is stored under:\n   169→\n   170→```text\n   171→.cc-manager/\n   172→  runs/\n   173→    <run-id>/\n   174→      manifest.json\n   175→      controller-decision.schema.json\n   176→      events.jsonl\n   177→      transcript.jsonl\n   178→      requests/\n   179→        req-0001/\n   180→          loop-0001/\n   181→            controller.prompt.txt\n   182→            controller.stdout.log\n   183→            controller.stderr.log\n   184→            controller.final.json\n   185→            worker.prompt.txt\n   186→            worker.stdout.log\n   187→            worker.stderr.log\n   188→            worker.final.json\n   189→```\n   190→\n   191→## Tests\n   192→\n   193→This repo includes fake Codex and Claude binaries plus integration tests that verify the exact visible control loop:\n   194→\n   195→- greeting -> controller replies directly -> `STOP`\n   196→- real work -> controller delegates -> Claude streams -> controller reviews -> controller delegates again -> `STOP`\n   197→- follow-up user message on the same run -> controller replies directly -> `STOP`\n   198→\n   199→Run them with:\n   200→\n   201→```bash\n   202→npm test\n   203→```\n   204→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"076ed951-b233-4f01-9f84-929dcf77822b","uuid":"ec1251f4-91f1-47e6-8b8d-17fd60fd735c","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"C:\\Users\\Server\\Downloads\\cc-manager-final\\cc-manager\\README.md","content":"# cc-manager\n\n`cc-manager` is an interactive terminal app that puts a **controller agent** (Codex CLI) in front of **Claude Code**.\n\nThe visible loop is:\n\n1. **User** sends a message in the shell.\n2. **Controller** (Codex) decides whether to:\n   - reply directly and stop, or\n   - launch **Claude Code** with the next worker prompt.\n3. **Claude Code** runs and its output is streamed live in the terminal.\n4. When Claude finishes, the **Controller** runs again, reviews the result and repository state, and decides the next Claude message or emits **STOP**.\n5. The shell stays open after **STOP** and waits for the next user instruction.\n\nThat makes the controller behave like a developer using Claude Code on behalf of the human manager.\n\n## What this implementation guarantees\n\n- The shell remains open after `STOP`.\n- The controller can answer simple messages directly without launching Claude Code.\n- When the controller delegates, the app prints the exact Claude prompt it is sending.\n- Claude output is streamed in real time.\n- After Claude exits, the controller gets another turn and can inspect the repository before deciding the next step.\n- The same Claude session is reused across worker turns in the same run.\n- Runs are persisted under `.cc-manager/runs/<run-id>` and can be resumed later.\n\n## Install\n\n```bash\nnpm install\nnpm link\n```\n\nNode 18.17+ is required.\n\n## Interactive shell\n\nStart the shell in the repository you want to manage:\n\n```bash\ncd /path/to/repo\ncc-manager\n```\n\nYou can also point it at another repo/state directory:\n\n```bash\ncc-manager --repo /path/to/repo --state-dir /path/to/state\n```\n\n### Shell behavior\n\n- If no run is attached, plain text starts a new run.\n- If a run is attached, plain text becomes the next user message for that run.\n- After the controller emits `STOP`, the shell stays attached to the run and waits for the next message.\n\n### Shell commands\n\n```text\n/help                Show help\n/new <message>       Start a brand new run and send the first message\n/resume <run-id>     Attach to an existing run\n/use <run-id>        Alias for /resume\n/run                 Continue an interrupted request in the current run\n/status              Show status for the attached run\n/list                List saved runs\n/logs [n]            Show the last n event lines for the attached run\n/detach              Detach from the current run\n/quit                Exit the shell\n```\n\n## One-shot usage\n\nStart a new run, process until `STOP`, then exit:\n\n```bash\ncc-manager run \"Please do fixes in this repository until all unit tests pass\"\n```\n\nResume an existing run with another user message:\n\n```bash\ncc-manager resume <run-id> \"Good job. Thank you\"\n```\n\nShow run status:\n\n```bash\ncc-manager status <run-id>\n```\n\nShow recent events:\n\n```bash\ncc-manager logs <run-id> --tail 80\n```\n\nList runs:\n\n```bash\ncc-manager list\n```\n\nVerify binaries:\n\n```bash\ncc-manager doctor\n```\n\n## Important defaults\n\n### Controller (Codex)\n\nBy default the controller uses:\n\n- `codex exec`\n- `codex exec resume <session-id>` after the first controller turn\n- `--json`\n- `--output-schema`\n- `--output-last-message`\n- `--ask-for-approval never`\n- `--sandbox workspace-write`\n\nThe controller prompt explicitly tells Codex to **inspect and verify only** and to avoid editing files itself. Claude Code is the worker that performs actual repository changes.\n\n### Worker (Claude Code)\n\nBy default the worker uses:\n\n- `claude -p`\n- `--output-format stream-json`\n- `--verbose`\n- `--include-partial-messages`\n- `--session-id <uuid>` for the first worker turn\n- `--resume <session-id>` on later worker turns\n- `--allowedTools \"Bash,Read,Edit\"`\n- a default appended system prompt that encourages concise progress narration\n\n## Useful options\n\n```text\n--repo <path>\n--state-dir <path>\n--codex-bin <path>\n--claude-bin <path>\n--controller-model <name>\n--controller-profile <name>\n--controller-sandbox <read-only|workspace-write|danger-full-access>\n--controller-config <key=value>            repeatable\n--controller-skip-git-repo-check\n--controller-extra-instructions <text>\n--worker-model <name>\n--worker-session-id <uuid>\n--worker-allowed-tools <rules>\n--worker-tools <rules>\n--worker-disallowed-tools <rules>\n--worker-permission-prompt-tool <name>\n--worker-max-turns <n>\n--worker-max-budget-usd <amount>\n--worker-add-dir <path>                    repeatable\n--worker-append-system-prompt <text>\n--raw-events\n--quiet\n```\n\n## Saved run layout\n\nEach run is stored under:\n\n```text\n.cc-manager/\n  runs/\n    <run-id>/\n      manifest.json\n      controller-decision.schema.json\n      events.jsonl\n      transcript.jsonl\n      requests/\n        req-0001/\n          loop-0001/\n            controller.prompt.txt\n            controller.stdout.log\n            controller.stderr.log\n            controller.final.json\n            worker.prompt.txt\n            worker.stdout.log\n            worker.stderr.log\n            worker.final.json\n```\n\n## Tests\n\nThis repo includes fake Codex and Claude binaries plus integration tests that verify the exact visible control loop:\n\n- greeting -> controller replies directly -> `STOP`\n- real work -> controller delegates -> Claude streams -> controller reviews -> controller delegates again -> `STOP`\n- follow-up user message on the same run -> controller replies directly -> `STOP`\n\nRun them with:\n\n```bash\nnpm test\n```\n","numLines":204,"startLine":1,"totalLines":204}}}}
